  "prompt": "What is the difference between C and C#?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between C and C#:\n\nC:\n1. Low-level programming language\n2. Procedural programming paradigm\n3. Manual memory management\n4. Compiled directly to machine code\n5. No built-in garbage collection\n6. Pointer manipulation is direct\n7. Used for system programming, embedded systems\n8. Developed in 1972 by Dennis Ritchie\n9. Minimal runtime support\n10. Platform-dependent compilation\n\nC#:\n1. High-level programming language\n2. Object-oriented programming paradigm\n3. Automatic memory management\n4. Compiled to intermediate language (IL)\n5. Automatic garbage collection\n6. Managed memory with limited pointer usage\n7. Used for Windows applications, web development, game development\n8. Developed in 2000 by Microsoft\n9. Runs on .NET framework/runtime\n10. Platform-independent (cross-platform with .NET Core)\n\nAdditional C# features:\n- Strong typing\n- LINQ support\n- Better type safety\n- More modern language constructs\n- Extensive standard library\n- Easy integration with Windows ecosystem\n- Support for async/await\n- More abstraction and high-level programming concepts\n\nC remains closer to hardware, while C# provides more developer productivity and convenience.",
